<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-320-640  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 320 640.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  April 9 1990 v24 n15 p100(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The anxiety of the on-line user. (choosing electronic informationservices)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Nimmer, Raymond T.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Choosing and maintaining external electronic data services for anorganization is difficult because the vast number of services andsheer volume of data available causes user confusion and anxiety.andO;Electronic-data users need workable structures for accessinginformation.andP;  Some managers believe they need only make dataservices available in a systematic manner, but no such method ofproviding data exists.andP;  Managers should discuss specific needswith users and make decisions accordingly.andP;  How much effort usersare willing to make to access a data service is a criticalconsideration.andP;  Some services go unused because their accessroutine are too complex for non-technical users to understand.andO;Search techniques are another major issue; users must be able tofind what information is most relevant to their needs.andP;  Anadditional concern is whether users can retrieve information bydownloading.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     System SelectionOn-LineInformation ServicesDecision MakingUser Needs.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>